post_text:
While creating our Return to School plans, schools across the state were given guidance from the Department of Health. One piece of guidance is this county data sheet, which gives us a number of cases in a 14-day period per 10,000 people.

These numbers then help guide us into choosing which policy we should follow (in-person, hybrid, or distance). Click the link below to view our county's current numbers or visit our website and click the article "Case Rate by County."

https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/stats/wschool.pdf

post_text: Congratulations to Ashlyn Meester on receiving the Jeans for Scholars Scholarship! During the year, staff at EPS can pay $20 to wear jeans on certain days throughout the year. That money goes into this scholarship, which is then awarded to one senior every year based on an application they fill out and hand in to a committee to vote on. Congrats again to Aslynn on receiving this from all the staff at EPS!

post_text: Youth Summer Baseball This message is for anyone who has a child in grades 3-8 (last school year) interested in playing baseball this summer. This summer, baseball travel teams will be run through the summer rec program. We are currently planning practice starting the week of June 15 with games starting the week of July 6. All games and practices will be at night. If your child is interested, please email Joe Kruger (j.kruger@isd511.net) with your child\'s name and previous years grade.

We know this is not the ideal way to spend your Senior Year of High School, so let´s give our Seniors some love!
... Meet Brandon!

Brandon is the son of Terri and Ken.
November 3rd is the day he would like cake for his birthday!
Classes this year for Brandon are: Weights and Wellness, Poetry, Media Literacy, Study Hall, Government, Economics, Vet Science and Art ll. Brandon’s favorite class is Weights and Wellness.
Some of Brandon’s favorites are hamburgers and the color blue.
His favorite past-time is basketball.
Advice to underclassmen is to stay in school!
Brandon’s future plans are to go to college and get a job.
Good Luck Brandon!!

post_text:
We know this is not the ideal way to spend your Senior Year of High School, so let´s give our Seniors some love!
... Meet Tylor!
He was born on November 1st.
Tylor has one brother, Cody, and two sisters, Kasey and Taylor.
The classes he is taking this year include: Weights and Wellness, Sociology, Plant Science, Natural Resource, Government, and Woods. With Weights and Wellness being his favorite.
A few of Tylor’s favorites are the color black and just driving around.
Tylor likes to play Rugby and Football, with Rugby being his favorite sport to play.
Tylor works at the Parkview Manor Nursing Home here in Ellsworth. He says the best part about his job is his co-workers.
As for his future plans, he plans on going to work after he graduates from Ellsworth High School.
Best wishes to your future, Tylor!

Today is a bittersweet day.

Today, we are beginning taping of a virtual graduation ceremony incase worse comes to worse and we are not able to have our Outdoor Ceremony in June.

Today, Seniors and their parents will be entering the doors of Ellsworth High School, with what might be their last time they step foot in this building as an Ellsworth Panther.

However, we are hearts a full, that we are able to create a memory for the students.

We are fortunate to be healthy, have the talents and willingness to think outside the box for something like this to be put together.

Lastly, as we gather together, we have a beautiful stage that was decorated and donated by Howies Floral. The sight of this stage, will surely bring large smiles and happy tears to the seniors & their families faces!

Thank you to all of the area businesses and community support throughout this time, and thank you for providing special memories for our seniors!
#ellsworthpanthers #pantherpride #seniors2020

post_text:
Distance Learning Organizational Tip: Use Google Calendar!

Students & Parents!

Within Google Classroom, teachers post due dates of assignments, announcments, zoom meetings, etc. Google Classroom will automatically set a reminder/task on your Google Calendar! You can sync your google calendar up with your cell phone and have it open on your chromebook. When the program is open, you will recieve a reminder notifcation of the upcoming due date, zoom call, etc! You can also create a "to do list" and edit it to best fit your needs.

In my adult life, I put almost everything on my Google Calendar- things like when pay day is, what bills are due when, when I have a family event, doctor appointment, second job duties, etc.

You can create a to do list within your Google Calendar, check out this video to figure out how! https://youtu.be/Gj4HG3gry58

Need help? Contact Ms. K by messaging the Facebook Page or Instagram Page, email katie.klosterbuer@ellsworth.mntm.org

Hey Students, grades 7-12th!
Most teachers are using Zoom and I have heard from some of you things like... "What is this zoom thing".

Let's get your zoom set up so you are ready for Monday. I've invited 7-12th Graders to join Ms. K & other teachers that are available at 4:30 PM on Sunday, March 29th.

Ms. K sent you a Google Calendar inviite to your email. In the email, you need to follow the Join Zoom Meeting" link located in the invitation or calendar information. Follow the prompts to set up a Zoom account- let it sync with your school google account.

Ms. K will be available from 4:30-5:30 PM to help you you set up and what to expect. Other teahcers will also be present if their schedule allows.

This is not required, but an option.

Ms. K will post a video Sunday, March 29th of how to get Zoom set up for those that want some extra help, or cannot make it to the video call.

On Thursday, the third graders did an experiment with germs. Different survaces were touched then we looked at the germs under a blacklight.

When the studetns were done, they wrote some cause and effect examples with washing your hands and not washing your hands. It takes more than just putting your hands under water to clean them.

If only our country would understand this concept as well, fitting activity to help the students understand what is currently happening in our communities, state and world.

While you are at home- continue to wash your hands thouroughly and get rid of as many unwanted germs as possible! The staff wants to see "our students" again soon!

#ellsworthpanthers #ellsworthpublicschools #watchuslearn

post_text:
Nobles County4-H is providing another Afterschool Program for students 2nd-7th Grade!

This program will run Tuesdays and Thursdays in April, from afterschool until 5 PM. The cost to attend is $15.

While at the Afterschool Program, the students will be learning about Engineering and the basic principles behind it. Each meeting they will be working on a different project!

You do not need to be a current, actively enrolled 4-H member, but will be asked to fill out an activty enrollment form for 4-H to ensure they have all the health and safety information!

Fylers went home this week with the students, and are do back to school by March 31st!

You won't want to miss this @nobles4h afterschool program!

Tomorrow the students will recieve incentives pending how many frogs they acculated during the week!

Which grade do you think accumulated the most frogs?!

The 8th grade art class had the opportunity to try out the Virtual Reality Kits available from the SWWC Service Cooperative. Rule #1: Remain seated - right Jacob? Rule #2 if you feel motion sickness coming on remove the goggles! Bringing this technology into the art room allowed students to learn about color, visit museums in Paris to view impressionist paintings, and the life works of Van Gogh. Then the students became the VR guides and we visited a dairy farm, Antarctica and the International Space Station. Learning with technology in the art room at EHS!

#ellsworthpublicschools #pantherpride #ellsworthpanthers #VR #creativearts #watchuslearn

World Foods students have been busy learning about the different regions of the United States, and what their food production looks like!

This week, they had their first lab where the 15 different students made 5 different recipeis depicting some of the regions of the United States and their common food production crops.

They made:
-Carne Asada Fries
-Scalloped Potatoes
-Succotash
-Southern Style Grits
-Marinated Artichokes

Interested in trying one of the recipes out, you're in luck! Visit the World Foods webpage on the Ellsworth School Website, and you can find the World Foods Recipes! Visit this link:https://www.ellsworth.mntm.org/faculty/katieklosterbuer/worldfoods.cfm

post_text:
Happy Tuesday Elementary Parents! Mr. D and Miss. A in P.E. are going to be trying somethings new to help with discipline problems. This is how it will work.

Step 1: Student will get a verbal warning.
Step 2: Student will sit out for a period of time in P.E.
Step 3: Student will fill out sheet of paper with Mr. D. or Miss. A. and will bring it home to go over with you. If you could go over it with your student and sign it that would be great! Then your student can bring it back the next time they are in P.E.

We are hoping this will help with your student being more independent and making better choices on their own! Thanks for all you do at home!

Mr. D. and Miss. A.
